## AI Pathfinding

Grid-based A* pathfinding and steering behaviors.

### Grid-Based Walkable Map
```typescript
// 0 = walkable, 1 = blocked
const GRID_SIZE = 32;
let walkableGrid: number[][] = []; // populated from tilemap
function buildNavGrid(tilemap: Phaser.Tilemaps.Tilemap, layer: Phaser.Tilemaps.TilemapLayer) {
  walkableGrid = [];
  for (let y = 0; y < tilemap.height; y++) {
    walkableGrid[y] = [];
    for (let x = 0; x < tilemap.width; x++) {
      const tile = layer.getTileAt(x, y);
      walkableGrid[y][x] = tile && tile.collides ? 1 : 0;
    }
  }
}
```

### Simple A* Implementation
```typescript
interface Node { x: number; y: number; g: number; h: number; f: number; parent?: Node; }
function astar(startX: number, startY: number, endX: number, endY: number): { x: number; y: number }[] {
  const open: Node[] = [{ x: startX, y: startY, g: 0, h: 0, f: 0 }];
  const closed: Set<string> = new Set();
  while (open.length > 0) {
    open.sort((a, b) => a.f - b.f);
    const current = open.shift()!;
    if (current.x === endX && current.y === endY) return reconstructPath(current);
    closed.add(`${current.x},${current.y}`);
    for (const [dx, dy] of [[0,1],[0,-1],[1,0],[-1,0]]) {
      const nx = current.x + dx, ny = current.y + dy;
      if (nx < 0 || ny < 0 || nx >= walkableGrid[0].length || ny >= walkableGrid.length) continue;
      if (walkableGrid[ny][nx] === 1 || closed.has(`${nx},${ny}`)) continue;
      const g = current.g + 1;
      const h = Math.abs(nx - endX) + Math.abs(ny - endY);
      open.push({ x: nx, y: ny, g, h, f: g + h, parent: current });
    }
  }
  return []; // no path
}
```

### Following the Path
```typescript
let pathIndex = 0; let path: { x: number; y: number }[] = [];
function followPath(enemy: Phaser.Physics.Arcade.Sprite, speed: number) {
  if (pathIndex >= path.length) { enemy.body!.setVelocity(0); return; }
  const target = path[pathIndex];
  const tx = target.x * GRID_SIZE + GRID_SIZE / 2;
  const ty = target.y * GRID_SIZE + GRID_SIZE / 2;
  if (Phaser.Math.Distance.Between(enemy.x, enemy.y, tx, ty) < 4) { pathIndex++; return; }
  this.physics.moveTo(enemy, tx, ty, speed);
}
```

### Tips
- Recalculate path every 500ms, not every frame
- Cache paths for enemies targeting the same location
- Use Manhattan distance heuristic for 4-directional, Euclidean for 8-directional
- Consider easystar.js library for production A* in Phaser

## Game Juice & Screen Effects

Small effects that make games feel great: screen shake, hit freeze, knockback.

### Hit Freeze (pause frame on impact)
```typescript
function hitFreeze(scene: Phaser.Scene, duration = 80) {
  scene.physics.world.pause();
  scene.time.delayedCall(duration, () => scene.physics.world.resume());
}
```

### Screen Shake Intensity Levels
```typescript
function shake(scene: Phaser.Scene, intensity: 'light' | 'medium' | 'heavy') {
  const cfg = { light: [100, 0.003], medium: [200, 0.008], heavy: [350, 0.015] };
  const [dur, amt] = cfg[intensity];
  scene.cameras.main.shake(dur, amt);
}
```

### Knockback
```typescript
function applyKnockback(target: Phaser.Physics.Arcade.Sprite, fromX: number, fromY: number, force = 300) {
  const angle = Phaser.Math.Angle.Between(fromX, fromY, target.x, target.y);
  target.body!.setVelocity(Math.cos(angle) * force, Math.sin(angle) * force);
}
```

### Sprite Flash on Hit
```typescript
function flashSprite(scene: Phaser.Scene, sprite: Phaser.GameObjects.Sprite, times = 4) {
  scene.tweens.add({
    targets: sprite, alpha: 0, duration: 80, yoyo: true, repeat: times,
    onComplete: () => sprite.setAlpha(1)
  });
}
```

### Slow Motion
```typescript
function slowMo(scene: Phaser.Scene, duration = 500) {
  scene.time.timeScale = 0.3;
  scene.physics.world.timeScale = 3; // inverse of time.timeScale
  scene.time.delayedCall(duration * 0.3, () => {
    scene.time.timeScale = 1; scene.physics.world.timeScale = 1;
  });
}
```

### Tips
- Combine shake + freeze + flash for satisfying hit feedback
- Use sparingly: too much juice becomes distracting
- Hit freeze should be very brief (50-100ms)
- Slow motion works great for kill cams or critical moments

